"Edwards T.L., Crucifix M., Harrison S.P.","Using the past to constrain the future: How the palaeorecord can improve estimates of global warming",2007,"Progress in Physical Geography","31","5",,"481","500",,,10.1177/0309133307083295,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-37049016660&partnerID=40&md5=8b39a29d3e92c79aac5b485edfb7f3da","School of Geographical Sciences, University of Bristol, University Road, Bristol BS8 1SS, United Kingdom; Institut d'Astronomie et de Géophysique Georges Lemaître, Université Catholique de Louvain, 2 Chemin du Cyclotron, Louvain B-1348, Belgium","Edwards, T.L., School of Geographical Sciences, University of Bristol, University Road, Bristol BS8 1SS, United Kingdom; Crucifix, M., Institut d'Astronomie et de Géophysique Georges Lemaître, Université Catholique de Louvain, 2 Chemin du Cyclotron, Louvain B-1348, Belgium; Harrison, S.P., School of Geographical Sciences, University of Bristol, University Road, Bristol BS8 1SS, United Kingdom","Climate sensitivity is defined as the change in global mean equilibrium temperature after a doubling of atmospheric CO2 concentration and provides a simple measure of global warming. An early estimate of climate sensitivity, 1.5-4.5°C, has changed little subsequently, including the latest assessment by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change. The persistence of such large uncertainties in this simple measure casts doubt on our understanding of the mechanisms of climate change and our ability to predict the response of the climate system to future perturbations. This has motivated continued attempts to constrain the range with climate data, alone or in conjunction with models. The majority of studies use data from the instrumental period (post-1850), but recent work has made use of information about the large climate changes experienced in the geological past. In this review, we first outline approaches that estimate climate sensitivity using instrumental climate observations and then summarize attempts to use the record of climate change on geological timescales. We examine the limitations of these studies and suggest ways in which the power of the palaeoclimate record could be better used to reduce uncertainties in our predictions of climate sensitivity. © 2007 SAGE Publications.","Climate change; Climate sensitivity; Future climates; Model evaluation; Palaeoclimate","air temperature; carbon dioxide; climate modeling; climate prediction; estimation method; geological record; global warming; Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change; paleoclimate; sensitivity analysis",,,,,,"Andronova, N.G., Schlesinger, M.E., Objective estimation of the probability density function for climate sensitivity (2001) Journal of Geophysical Research, 106, pp. 22605-22611; Annan, J.D., Hargreaves, J.C., Using multiple observationally-based constraints to estimate climate sensitivity (2006) Geophysical Research Letters, 33, pp. L06704; Annan, J.D., Hargreaves, J.C., Ohgaito, R., Abe-Ouchi, A., Emori, S., Efficiently constraining climate sensitivity with ensembles of paleoclimate, simulations (2005) SOLA, 1, pp. 181-184; Arrhenius, S., On the influence of carbonic acid in the air upon the temperature of the ground (1896) Philosophical Magazine and Journal of Science, 41, pp. 239-276; Ballantyne, A.P., Lavine, M., Crowley, T.J., Liu, J., Baker, P.B., Meta-analysis of tropical surface temperatures during the Last Glacial Maximum (2005) Geophysical Research Letters, 32, pp. L05712; Barnett, T.P., Pierce, D.W., Schnur, R., Detection of anthropogenic climate change in the world's oceans (2001) Science, 292, pp. 270-274; Barron, E.J., A warm, equable Cretaceous: The nature of the problem (1983) Earth Science Reviews, 19, pp. 305-338; Barron, E.J., (1993) American Geophysical Union Spring Meeting, , Paper presented at the, Baltimore, 24-8 May; Barron, E.J., Fawcett, P.J., Peterson, W.H., Pollard, D., Thompson, S.L., A 'simulation' of mid-Cretaceous climate (1995) Paleoceanograp